It was with a mixture of profound
sadness and disgust that I read Elaine
Clifford’s story about the national organ
shortage (Pitt News, Jan. 26). Sadness for
those who are sick and dying; disgust for
the U.S. Congress.

On the one hand, it’s terribly tragic
that 10 people die each day waiting for
organs while, according to a quick calcu-
lation from Ms. Clifford’s ﬁgures, almost
19 suitable donors die each day and take
their organs with them.

On the other hand, it’s disgusting that
this problem is all caused by our own
well—intentioned but hopelessly ignorant
government officials.

Federal legislators, in the 1984
National Organ Transplantation Act,
made it illegal for people to receive
money for their own organs, even if
they’re to be harvested only after death.
Their desire was to prevent poor people
from selling a kidney while still alive and
thus endangering their future health. But
their sweeping legislation also prohibited
people from selling the ﬁiture rights to
their organs, effectively choking off any
possibility that a free market could devel-
op to handle the demand for human
organs.

I envision a system where healthy
people would receive either a lump sum

payment for the future rights to harvest
their organs, once deceased, or yearly
payments contingent upon their maintain-
ing good health.

Ms. Clifford quotes two Pitt students
who are committed to being organ
donors, but who are afraid that emergency
medical personnel would be less likely to
save them if they knew they were donors
and someone “important” were waiting
for an organ. She also quotes a UPMC
transplant surgeon as saying their fear
was unfounded, but understandable.

A free market for organs would elim-'

inate such fears by eliminating the short-

age. Being offered cold hard cash, up 
front, to “do the right thing” would be just,
the incentive to get many folks to sell tire?‘
rights to harvest their organs upon death."

And the increased supply would end the
fears that they’ll be sacriﬁced for the likes
of some wealthy oil sheik or powerful
politician (like former Gov. Bob Casey).
More importantly, people wouldn’t die
for lack of organs.

Now we’ve got PennDOT and the
IRS sending us organ donor cards.
President Ronald Reagan may not have
walked the walk, but his talk was right on
the money: Government isn’t the solu-
tion, it’s the problem. "

